+## AtlasIT – AI Assistant Comprehensive Guide
+Goal: Equip AI coding agents to make safe, high‑leverage changes fast. This document is intentionally thorough. Prefer ACTIONABLE + CURRENT state over roadmap speculation. If something is in mockups but absent in code (compliance engine, marketplace, risk matrix, policy editor), treat it as NOT IMPLEMENTED.
+
+---
+### 1. Current Implemented Surface (Reality Snapshot)
+Active Cloudflare Workers: `onboarding/`, `ai-orchestrator/`, `documentation-worker/`. Shared utilities + runtime hardening code under `src/runtime/**`. Experimental UI prototype lives in `console-app/` (SvelteKit) – avoid coupling backend changes to UI assumptions unless tests assert them.
+
+Non‑implemented (do NOT create endpoints ad‑hoc): compliance scoring API, policy engine, marketplace, risk assessment matrix, advanced directory/JML flows. Legacy Ignite/MCP materials retained in `LEGACY.md` – append-only unless an explicit migration task exists.
+
+---
+### 2. High-Level Architecture & Data Flows
+Edge‑native design: each Worker is a narrow responsibility boundary; shared logic (logging, env validation, dynamic feature registry) is imported where needed.
+Bindings (declared in `wrangler.toml`) drive persistence & runtime capabilities:
+- KV: sessions (`KV_SESSIONS`), generic cache (`KV_CACHE`), flags (`KV_FEATURE_FLAGS`), MCP store (`MCP_STORE`).
+- D1: core/audit/compliance DBs (`ATLAS_CORE_DB`, `ATLAS_AUDIT_DB`, etc.) – some referenced but not fully utilized yet (future compliance schema).
+- R2: artifacts/evidence/policies buckets (`atlas_artifacts`, `atlas_evidence`, `atlas_policies`). Health responses append R2 bucket usage metrics when present (see orchestrator tests).
+Request lifecycle typically: parse headers (API key), validate env, perform KV/D1/R2 operations, append diagnostics (never remove existing fields), return JSON.
+
+---
+### 3. Runtime Hardening (Dynamic Feature System)
+Location: `src/runtime/features/registry.ts` plus related modules (`scans/`, `jobs/`, `data/`, `routes/`).
+Feature kinds currently in play: `scan`, `job`, `data`, `route` (route registry utility). Each feature registers early on import using `registerFeature()` which validates presence of `id`, `kind`, and method contracts (`run`, `fetch`, or `schedule`).
+Snapshot access: `getFeatures(kind?)` returns an immutable array; downstream diagnostics and health endpoints consume snapshots to produce append-only metadata.
+Timeout & gating env vars (Phase A/B):
+- Scans: `ENABLED_SCAN_TYPES` allowlist overrides any disabled list; `DISABLED_SCAN_TYPES` applies only if allowlist absent.
+- Capability (future phases): `ENABLE_CAPABILITIES`, `DISABLE_CAPABILITIES` (planned – DO NOT invent yet).
+- Default timeout: `SCAN_MODULE_TIMEOUT_DEFAULT` or per‑module override `SCAN_MODULE_TIMEOUT_<UPPER_ID>`.
+Append-only health augmentation: new sections like `dynamicRegistry`, `scanPerf`, future `jobs`, `dataProviders` MUST add keys without renaming existing ones. Tests expect backwards compatibility.
+
+---
+### 4. Scan Runtime Deep Dive
+Files: `src/runtime/scans/service.ts`, modules in `src/runtime/scans/modules/*` (e.g. `headers.ts`, `ssl.ts`, `info.ts`, `threatIntel.ts`, `cve.ts`).
+Key exports:
+- `getAvailableScanTypes(config?)`
+- `runScan(id, url, ctx, config?)`
+- `runFullScan(url, ctx, config?)`
+- `resolveEnabledScanIds(config, { includeFull })`
+Enable/disable precedence:
+1. `ENABLED_SCAN_TYPES` (comma list explicit allowlist)
+2. `DISABLED_SCAN_TYPES` (comma list denylist if allowlist absent)
+3. Defaults (all core modules) if neither set.
+Full scan: executes all enabled modules, aggregates findings, attaches per-module timing & counts. Logs tagged `[runtime:scan.module.completed]` and aggregate completion.
+
+---
+### 5. Jobs & Data Providers (Phase B)
+Jobs: registered with `kind: 'job'`, include `schedule.intervalMs` and async `run()`; first execution delayed until interval passes (prevent cold start burst). Metrics tracked in-memory (runs, errors, lastRunAt, avgMs, totalMs). Snapshot accessor (`schedulerSnapshot()`) used for future diagnostic append.
+Data providers: `kind: 'data'` with `fetch(params, ctx)` returning lightweight computed metadata (e.g. `site-metadata` summarizing registry version & counts). Keep providers side-effect free & fast.
+Health representation of jobs/providers is staged; append-only principle applies when surfaces are added.
+
+---
+### 6. Route Registry & Introspection
+Utility module (e.g. `src/runtime/routes/registerRoute.ts`): handlers self-register (method, path, description). Endpoint `/api/_routes` returns snapshot used by tooling / UI for dynamic discovery. Maintain path stability; append new routes—do not repurpose existing IDs.
+
+---
+### 7. Secrets & Environment Validation
+Commands:
+- Set secret: `wrangler secret put <NAME> --env <env>` (e.g. `SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL`, `AI_GATEWAY_TOKEN`).
+- Validate config: `npm run validate:env` (fails fast on missing required bindings / secrets).
+Never hardcode secret values. Diagnostics on startup log missing bindings (`[bindings] Missing Cloudflare bindings detected`). Block production deploy until resolved.
+
+---
+### 8. Development & Execution Workflow
+Install deps: `npm install`
+Type safety: `npm run typecheck`
+Unit tests: `npm run test:unit` (Vitest; covers workers + shared runtime).
+Predeploy gate: `npm run predeploy` (aggregates env validation, typecheck, tests).
+Local multi-worker dev: `npm run dev:core` (or individual `npm run dev:onboarding`).
+Cloudflare worker preview: inside target worker folder run `wrangler dev`.
+Container (Codex) build & guard: task `codex:build image` builds Dockerfile `docker/Dockerfile.codex`; run guard script `docker/codex-exec.sh` to enforce protected globs from `codex-work.json`.
+
+---
+### 9. Testing Conventions & Patterns
+Framework: Vitest. Patterns from `ai-orchestrator/orchestrator.test.ts` & `tests/orchestrator.test.ts`:
+- API key gating validated by sending/omitting `x-api-key` header (expect 401 unauthorized vs 200/403 accepted/pending states).
+- Health endpoint tests assert presence of stable fields (`status`, `service`, `requestId`) + appended resources (`r2.atlas_policies`, etc.). Write tests defensively: allow multiple acceptable status codes when async workflows can yield 403 vs 200.
+- Idempotent / concurrency control (ETL run): first POST returns 202/200; immediate second call expects 200 duplicate or 409 already_running.
+When extending endpoints: update or add tests verifying appended JSON keys without breaking existing shape. DO NOT rewrite assertions to require new keys if older deployments may legitimately omit them (use conditional checks).
+
+---
+### 10. Safe Change Checklist (Before Opening PR)
+1. Confirm scope exists (no speculative compliance endpoints).
+2. Add/adjust minimal tests (feature registration, health append, endpoint logic).
+3. Run: `npm run validate:env`, `npm run typecheck`, `npm run test:unit`.
+4. For dynamic runtime changes: ensure registry snapshot logs (`[runtime:registry.snapshot]`) still emit once per build.
+5. Verify health payload keys only appended; diff serialized JSON if needed.
+6. If modifying guarded paths (policy/auth/runtime): update `codex-work.json` in same commit.
+7. Keep prompt context small: prefer referencing `codex-context.trimmed.txt` over embedding large file bodies.
+
+---
+### 11. Feature Registration Contract (Deep Reference)
+`registerFeature(feature)` requirements:
+- Mandatory fields: `id`, `kind`.
+- For scans: supply `run(url, ctx, config?)`.
+- For jobs: include `schedule.intervalMs` (>= 30s recommended) + `run()`.
+- For data providers: implement `fetch(params, ctx)`.
+Optional metadata: `version`, `meta` (object), `provides` / `requires` capability tags, lifecycle hooks (`activate`, `deactivate`), `health()` partial status builder.
+Validation rejects missing contracts with log `feature.invalid` (reason e.g. `scan-missing-run`). Returned snapshot is frozen; avoid direct mutation.
+
+---
+### 12. Observability & Diagnostics
+Endpoints: `/api/_diagnostics` (scan timings p50/p95/avg, timeout counts), `/api/admin/reload` (rebuild registry snapshot with debounce, returns version & enabledScanIds). Logging tags: `runtime:scan.module.completed`, `scan.full.completed`, `runtime:registry.snapshot`, `job.run.error`. When extending: follow existing tag format `<domain>.<category>.<event>` for consistency.
+Performance baselines: keep added scan modules fast (<100ms typical). If slow or high variance, include structured timing in diagnostics rather than ad‑hoc console prints.
+
+---
+### 13. Docker / Codex Guardrails
+Protected paths declared in `codex-work.json`; guard script aborts if modifications occur without updating the policy. For large refactors split changes so guard policy updates remain reviewable. Avoid expanding prompts with entire README—use trimmed context generation (`npm run codex:context`).
+
+---
+### 14. Common Pitfalls & How to Avoid Them
+- Premature compliance endpoint creation → Check README roadmap; open issue first.
+- Health payload key replacement → Always append; never rename existing keys.
+- Secret leakage in logs → Use redaction / avoid printing full values.
+- Overly granular feature registration → Group related tiny scans into one module to reduce overhead.
+- Blocking jobs on cold start → Respect delayed first run design; do not force immediate execution unless absolutely required.
+
+---
+### 15. Example: Adding a New Scan Module (Headers Hardening Variant)
+1. Create `src/runtime/scans/modules/securityHeadersExtended.ts` exporting `{ id: 'securityHeadersExtended', kind: 'scan', version, run() }`.
+2. Inside `run()`, measure start/end time; return findings with concise structure.
+3. Import module in central scan bootstrap so registration occurs.
+4. Add unit test asserting `getAvailableScanTypes()` includes new id when not gated.
+5. Extend diagnostics test to expect presence (conditionally) without breaking others.
+6. Run predeploy steps; ensure health response unchanged except appended `scanPerf.modules.securityHeadersExtended`.
+
+---
+### 16. Example: Adding a Background Job
+1. File: `src/runtime/jobs/metricsSnapshot.ts` registering `{ kind: 'job', id: 'metrics-snapshot', schedule: { intervalMs: 30000 }, run() }`.
+2. Track minimal in-memory metrics; expose via accessor for future diagnostics.
+3. Test: scheduler registers and executes at least once (use fake timers if available; else assert run invocation after delay).
+4. Health augmentation (if needed) appended under `dynamicRegistry.jobs` later—do NOT introduce prematurely.
+
+---
+### 17. Commit & PR Conventions
+Commit message format: `type(scope): message` (e.g. `feat(runtime): add data provider snapshot`). Types: `feat`, `fix`, `chore`, `refactor`, `test`, `docs`. Scope = folder or domain (`runtime`, `onboarding`, `orchestrator`, `agents`). Keep commits focused; large multi-domain changes are harder to review & revert.
+PR checks: ensure tests added for behavioral changes; no secrets; health shape backward compatible; codex guard updates where necessary.
+
+---
+### 18. When Unsure / Decision Path
+1. Search for precedent (similar file in `scans/modules` / `jobs/` / tests).
+2. If no pattern, draft minimal addition + test harness; keep public surface narrow.
+3. Ask for clarification only if a needed abstraction truly absent (avoid speculative frameworks).
+4. Prefer incremental PR: one feature + tests rather than batching multiple unrelated changes.
+
+---
+### 19. Prompt Hygiene for AI-Driven Changes
+Use `codex-context.trimmed.txt` + targeted source files only. Avoid embedding entire README or large multi-module code unless absolutely required for semantic diff. Keep prompt size <25k characters to minimize truncation and token overflow. Reference file paths directly (`src/runtime/features/registry.ts`) instead of copying contents.
+
+---
+### 20. Guardrails Recap (TL;DR)
+- Append-only JSON contract.
+- Never hardcode secrets.
+- Respect gating precedence (`ENABLED_SCAN_TYPES` > `DISABLED_SCAN_TYPES`).
+- Register features early; avoid mutation post-snapshot.
+- Tests must pass (`npm run predeploy`) before proposing changes.
+- Update guard policy if touching protected paths.
+
+This guide is authoritative for current architecture. If a section becomes outdated, update both code + this document in the same PR to keep agents aligned.
+
+---
+### 21. AI Operating Modes (Planner / Orchestrator / Product Steward)
+Define explicit working modes to reduce ambiguity:
+- Planner: Break user objective into epics → stories → actionable file edits; produce dependency map & risk notes. Output: structured TODO with states (not-started/in-progress/completed) aligning to repository domains.
+- Orchestrator: Sequence multi-worker changes (e.g. scan module + health test). Ensures environment validation, test coverage, append-only contract preserved before merging.
+- Product Steward: Evaluate requested feature against roadmap & guardrails; confirm non-implemented domains are deferred; suggest smallest viable slice + acceptance criteria & success metrics.
+Switch modes deliberately; log mode in PR description or issue comment for transparency.
+
+### 22. Planning Framework (5-Step)
+1. Clarify Scope: Identify whether request touches runtime, worker endpoint, or agent script. Reject speculative compliance scope.
+2. Inventory Artifacts: List impacted files (e.g. `src/runtime/scans/service.ts`, tests path, `wrangler.toml` if bindings required).
+3. Risk Scoring: Consider JSON contract impact, secret handling, performance (<100ms scan target), guardrail modifications.
+4. Plan Validation: Draft test additions (happy path + at least one edge: missing key, timeout scenario).
+5. Execution Order: Environment validation → feature registration → tests → diagnostics append → docs update.
+
+### 23. Decision Matrix (Implement vs Defer)
+Implement now if: existing pattern present, no new binding type, health contract only appended, performance within baseline, tests straightforward.
+Defer if: introduces new compliance concept, requires schema migrations, adds persistent telemetry store, or changes auth surfaces.
+Escalate (ask maintainer) if: conflicting gating rules, large refactor to protected paths, unclear capability taxonomy.
+
+### 24. Codex Collaboration Workflow
+Use trimmed context (`codex-context.trimmed.txt`) + specific source files. For multi-phase features:
+- Phase Proposal: Add numbered section to prompt-update sheet (append-only) describing delta.
+- Implementation: Restrict edits to declared modules; run guard script to ensure no protected path drift.
+- Verification: Compare snapshot logs (`runtime:registry.snapshot`) count diff; ensure no renames in health JSON.
+- Telemetry: Add entries following proposed shape; maintain ring buffer size; update diagnostics tests.
+
+### 25. Structured TODO & State Management
+Maintain a machine-readable TODO list (IDs, titles, status). Transition one item at a time to `in-progress`. Complete before starting next. Reflect cross-dependency (e.g. test depends on registration). This mirrors orchestrator concurrency controls (avoid duplicate ETL run situations) and reduces race conditions in AI-driven edits.
+
+### 26. Acceptance Criteria Pattern
+For each change provide: Inputs → Process → Outputs → Edge Cases.
+Example (scan module):
+- Inputs: url string, env gating.
+- Process: run security headers audit, measure duration, catch timeout.
+- Outputs: findings array, timing metadata, status code in diagnostics.
+- Edge Cases: unreachable URL (graceful error), timeout (synthetic finding), no findings (empty array, still record timing).
+
+### 27. Performance & Telemetry Guidelines
+Scan modules <100ms typical; if >250ms p95 over 10 runs, document rationale & optimization plan. Add `status: 'slow'` flag only in telemetry buffer (append-only) – do NOT alter existing health keys. Avoid heavy external IO in jobs; favor cached provider fetches.
+
+### 28. Product Stewardship Heuristics
+When user requests broad feature (e.g. "add compliance scoring"), respond with: current state (not implemented), minimal viable step (e.g. stub data provider returning static score), risk summary (avoid implying production readiness), and migration path (data provider → real D1 schema next phase). Always cite guardrails (append-only, no new endpoints without roadmap alignment).
+
+### 29. PR / Issue Template Enhancements (Recommended)
+Add optional sections:
+- Mode: Planner | Orchestrator | Product Steward
+- Summary (≤280 chars)
+- Affected Paths
+- Append-Only Impact (Y/N; list keys appended)
+- Performance Considerations
+- Test Additions
+- Rollback Strategy
+These enable AI + human rapid review alignment.
+
+### 30. Expanded Risk & Scope Guardrails
+Risk Categories:
+- Contract Risk: health JSON breaking change → BLOCK
+- Secret Risk: new env var required without validation update → BLOCK
+- Performance Risk: p95 > target with no mitigation → WARN
+- Scope Creep: introduces roadmap phase feature prematurely → DEFER
+Classification influences decision matrix outcomes.
+
+### 31. Failure & Recovery Patterns
+If tests fail: capture failing assertion text, categorize (contract vs logic vs env). Attempt ≤3 focused patches. On telemetry mismatch: dump before/after timing summary; never silence failure by removing test.
+Rollback: revert module file + remove registration import; confirm tests green (absence tolerated). Document rollback in PR with "Reverted Scan Module X due to contract conflict".
+
+### 32. Multi-Worker Coordination
+Sequential changes across workers: update shared util first, run unit tests, then apply worker-specific endpoint augmentation. Avoid simultaneous edits that obscure root cause of failures (mirrors orchestrator concurrency principles). Use commit segmentation: `feat(runtime): add util`, then `feat(orchestrator): use util`.
+
+### 33. Capability Tag Future-Proofing
+When adding `provides`/`requires` lists pre-capability gating, ensure tags are stable, lowercase with dashes (`headers-security`, `evidence-export`). Document any new tag inside prompt-update sheet section (append-only). Avoid semantic overloading (one tag = one conceptual capability).
+
+### 34. AI Self-Audit Routine
+Before marking task complete:
+1. Re-run tests.
+2. Grep for hardcoded secrets patterns (`API_KEY=` like substrings).
+3. Diff health payload old vs new for appended-only compliance.
+4. Estimate performance impact (qualitative if metrics unavailable).
+5. Log summary in PR description.
+
+### 35. Continuous Improvement Hooks (Optional Enhancements)
+Potential additions (create only if requested):
+- `scripts/ai/self-audit.ts` executing routine above.
+- `tools/generate-ai-plan.ts` scaffolding TODO list from issue JSON.
+- `docs/AI_MODES.md` with examples for each operating mode.
+Treat these as incremental, low-risk; avoid bundling with runtime feature changes.
+
+### 36. Example Planner Output (Template)
+```yaml
+mode: planner
+objective: "Add extended security headers scan"
+epics:
+	- id: E1
+		title: Create module file
+		stories:
+			- id: S1
+				title: Implement run() with timing
+	- id: E2
+		title: Register & gate module
+		stories:
+			- id: S2
+				title: Import in scans bootstrap
+	- id: E3
+		title: Testing & diagnostics
+		stories:
+			- id: S3
+				title: Unit test inclusion
+			- id: S4
+				title: Diagnostics append validation
+risks:
+	- contract: "Must not rename existing health keys"
+	- performance: "Target <100ms p95"
+success_metrics:
+	- "Test passes for new scan id"
+	- "Health payload contains scanPerf.modules.securityHeadersExtended"
+rollback: "Remove module import & file; revert tests"
+```
+
+### 37. Orchestrator Mode Checklist
+1. Validate env & bindings.
+2. Confirm no protected path violation (codex guard dry run).
+3. Apply change in smallest diff.
+4. Add/adjust tests.
+5. Run predeploy suite.
+6. Self-audit & document.
+7. Await review or proceed to deployment script.
+
+### 38. Product Steward Response Template
+If feature request outside current surface:
+```
+Status: Not implemented.
+Minimal viable slice: <describe small provider/placeholder>.
+Risks: contract, scope creep.
+Recommendation: implement slice only after roadmap phase ticket exists.
+Next step: open issue with capability tag + acceptance criteria.
+```
+
+### 39. Mode Switching Guidance
+Allow only one active mode per task context. Planner → Orchestrator after plan acceptance; Orchestrator → Product Steward only if scope drift detected mid-execution. Record transition in commit message footers (`Mode-Transition: planner->orchestrator`).
+
+### 40. Living Document Maintenance
+When adding new operating guidance: append new numbered section; never edit existing text except to correct factual errors (include note: `Errata: section <n>`). Keep additions <250 lines per update to preserve readability.
+
+---
+End of extended AI operation guidance.
